Policy Iteration
Value Iteration, ADP, GPI
You sum every action-value multiplied by the probability to commit that action (the policy)

pi(a|s) is the probability of taking action a in state s under policy pi
Can be solved by simultaneous linear equations if MDP is known
Can update values of Vpi (in-place) with update rules
Calc Vpi with update rule below
Having solved for Vpi, now improve the policy.
Change one action (a). Instead of doing pi(s), take action, a and then continue with policy, pi.
Bounce between policy evaluation and policy improvement
Iterate policy evauation until converged ( V(s) = r + gamma * V(s) )
Improve policy (see if any changes to pi(s) after above converged V(s) values)
When policy is converged (i.e. no more pi(s) changes), code is done
NOT VERY EFFICIENT
Stop PolicyEvaluation after just one sweep
Combines Policy Improvement and Truncated Policy Evaluation
Terminates when changes are small enough.
Can possibly improve convergence with extra policy evaluation steps before the policy improvement step.
Policy Iteration has 2 steps:
1) Policy Evaluation - Make Value Function Consistent with Current Policy
2) Policy Improvement - Make Policy Greedy wrt Current Value Function
GPI - various approaches to the two steps.
For large state spaces, might want to avoid the complete "sweep" of all states in the Evaluation step
First Visit vs Every Visit
Every Visit is more interesting for function evaluation and eligibility traces.

Every Visit is the same except for the check of St occurring earlier in the episode
Model-Based: Learn Tand R (the model) and use them to estimate MDP and solve it. (with planning)
Model-Free: simply learn Q(s,a), the value of each action in each state (e.g. QLearning) from trial and error
Models can make predictions about the next state and reward, Model-Free cannot.
Often tasks transition from Model-Free to Model-Based.
Model-Based uses probabilities of the MDP, Model-Free does not.
e.g. QLearning update does NOT use probability, Policy Improvement does.
Target Policy is GREEDY... i.e. the policy to be learned
Behavior Policy is the policy followed during learning (e.g epsilon greedy, random, etc.)
If Behavior policy == Target Policy, then it's an On-Policy method.

For example Epsilon-Greedy
